00:09:55.000 --> 00:10:01.000
It's a, maybe not being people notice, it's a port of an R package called GT.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:06.000
Not that important, but like the idea is as good as it was then.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:12.000
You want display tables, what I call them, essentially summary tables, like static tables.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:18.000
And you want to present them, say, in a notebook or say, like in some other publishable document as HTML.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:23.000
We also have a LaTeX output format. But the idea is you compose tables step by step.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:28.000
You know, you add a header, you want a title, you get that too.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:34.000
You structure the table. You can format different cells, like usually entire columns of cells.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:42.000
And you can also style a table, which could be like, you know, like changing orders, adding cell backgrounds, things like that.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:48.000
And really the idea is like to make a table that you might see like in a print publication.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:52.000
But using your data, like directly, like using a data frame.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:57.000
So you have the data in a form which is amenable to a summary table.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:03.000
And then in just a few like method calls, you've got the table.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:06.000
You know what's, what's, yeah, that's awesome.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:11.000
What strikes me about this, you know, when we had our conversation last year,

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:19.000
is just how much more there is to think about with tables than, you know, just an Excel-like thing.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:24.000
I came away realizing that it goes way deeper and there's a lot more nuance.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:32.000
It felt a little bit like, oh gosh, I can't remember the guy's name, but I'm sure you both have seen his books.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:36.000
